english:
  title: A Preface for the Reverend Dharma Master Gyeong
  author: Kim Su-on
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In my pursuit of the subtle Way, friends have turned away and old companions grown distant, leaving my gate so lonely one might scatter nets to catch sparrows. Then came the Reverend Gyeong, and I rejoiced greatly, offering him the seat of honor. Before our conversation had barely begun, he perceived that I delight in amusing people with clever words, and pressing a blank paper into my hands, requested that I compose a preface. Happily, I took up my brush and did not shrink from the task, despite the rough stumbling of my words.

    Those sages who renounce the world—their distinction lies not merely in their conduct's loftiness, but in how their minds differ from common souls. What is companionship with monkeys, cranes, deer, and elk compared to dwelling among robed and crowned scholars and ministers? What is sustenance drawn from clouds and mists, nourished on sacred mushrooms and bitter herbs—draining the flesh—compared to the comfort of rice and silk, sitting in palatial halls, coursing grand thoroughfares? And what are craggy peaks, dark caverns, and treacherous cliffs compared to the pleasures of cities, walls, and open roads?

    Yet to spurn the latter for the former, to flee this place so eagerly as if court robes were worn while sitting in mud and ash—is this not to love what people despise and despise what people love, thereby violating human nature itself?

    Indeed, the ancients produced hermits who withdrew and dwelled hidden, unmarked by commerce. Yet all did so in times when the Way had failed, when virtue could find no expression. They hung up their caps, wore garments of rushes by streams, wandered among rocks and springs, bent to the fields—pursuing solitary righteousness alone.

    But when sage-kings rule on high and worthy ministers govern below, when governance flourishes and rites and music arise, when courts run clear and people prosper—what should scholars then do? They should don official regalia, receive honors, fulfill their offices, work to extend benevolence, to build achievements in their time and spread their fame through ages unending.

    In such an age, to insist upon retreat and permanent withdrawal violates not only human nature but also the very principles of society. The Reverend Gyeong now prepares to leave for distant mountains and great rivers, to dim his traces in obscurity. He told me of monks of merit who wish to accompany him. For this reason, I rebuked him sharply, criticizing such hidden lives, yet he may question these companions and report their answers to me. Then Gwae-ae would surely pen further words of censure.

    Alas, I have long guarded the subtle Way within these humble walls, yet the Reverend has sought me out here, laying bare the question of hiddenness and engagement through words and prose. Perhaps my subtle understanding still glimmers too brightly, not yet entirely shrouded in perfect darkness.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: '玄武門 (Xuanwu Gate): Historical reference to hanging one''s official cap at the gate, symbolizing retirement from office.'
  - key: ''
    value: '川澤 (streams and marshes): Classical trope for withdrawal from society into nature.'
  - key: ''
    value: '乖崖 (Gwae-ae): Likely a reference to a historical figure known for principled criticism, used here to suggest the author''s own stern moral stance.'
  - key: ''
    value: The final paradox about 玄 (the subtle Way) and 白 (whiteness/brightness) suggests the author's ironic concern that his own genuine withdrawal remains too visible, too obvious to the world.
